14 SECTION 2. KRS 433.902 IS REPEALED AND REENACTED TO READ
15 AS FOLLOWS:
16 A person shall not engage or attempt to engage in business in this Commonwealth as a
17 secondary metals recycler unless licensed in accordance with Sections 1 to 12 of this
18 Act.
19 SECTION 3. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 433 IS CREATED TO
20 READ AS FOLLOWS:
21 (1) An applicant for licensure as a secondary metals recycler shall file a written
22 application under oath on a form provided by the commission. An applicant who
23 owns more than one (1) secondary metals recycling location shall file an
24 application for each location. Upon approval of the application and payment of
25 the application fee, the commission shall issue a license to the applicant.
26 (2) Any person listed on an application for a secondary metals recycler business
27 license shall be at least eighteen (18) years of age prior to the date the application
Page 3 of 53
BR123800.100 - 1238 - XXXX 3/11/2026 3:19 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1238
1 is submitted.
2 (3) (a) Prior to approval of the application, the commission shall require a name-
3 based background check on each applicant.
4 (b) Each applicant shall provide written authorization to the Department of
5 Kentucky State Police to perform a name-based background check and
6 release the results to the commission.
7 (c) Any request for a name-based background check shall be on a form or
8 through a process approved by the Department of Kentucky State Police,
9 which may charge a fee to be paid by the applicant in an amount no greater
10 than the actual cost of processing the request.
11 (d) The commission shall not issue a license to an applicant if the name-based
12 background check results reveal that within the last five (5) years the
13 applicant has been convicted of, or entered a plea of guilty, an Alford plea,
14 or a plea of nolo contendere to, a felony involving theft, larceny, dealing in
15 stolen property, receiving stolen property, burglary, embezzlement, or
16 obtaining property by false pretenses, any felony drug offense, or
17 intentionally violating the laws of the Commonwealth relating to licensure
18 as a secondary metals recycler.
19 (4) The application for a license shall be in a form prescribed by the commission and
20 shall contain at a minimum the following:
21 (a) The name, address, and telephone number of the secondary metals
22 recycling business;
23 (b) The name, home address, and telephone number of each applicant;
24 (c) The address of each secondary metals recycling business owned by the
25 applicant;
26 (d) Contact information for the purposes of Section 9 of this Act;
27 (e) The nature or character of the goods, wares, merchandise, or services to be
Page 4 of 53
BR123800.100 - 1238 - XXXX 3/11/2026 3:19 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1238
1 offered by the applicant;
2 (f) Any criminal convictions within the past five (5) years related to theft, stolen
3 property, or other pecuniary crimes of the applicant; and
4 (g) A statement of whether the applicant has previously been denied a license
5 under this section or if the applicant has had a previous license revoked or
6 suspended, and if so, the reasons or circumstances surrounding the denial,
7 revocation, or suspension of the license.
8 (5) Each application for a license as a secondary metals recycler shall be
9 accompanied by a reasonable fee as established by the commission.
10 (6) Licenses issued by the commission shall be subject to annual renewal and shall
11 expire unless renewed upon payment of a reasonable renewal fee in the manner
12 prescribed by the commission.
13 (7) A secondary metals recycler business license shall be conspicuously displayed at
14 each secondary metals recycling business owned by a secondary metals recycler.
15 SECTION 4. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 433 IS CREATED TO
16 READ AS FOLLOWS:
17 (1) The commission shall oversee, manage, and enforce all penalties and disciplinary
18 actions related to violations committed by secondary metals recyclers. The
19 commission may coordinate with local law enforcement agencies to ensure
20 compliance with Sections 1 to 12 of this Act.
21 (2) The commission shall maintain a centralized record of violations and
22 enforcement actions taken under Sections 1 to 12 of this Act and shall make the
23 records available to law enforcement agencies and regulatory bodies as permitted
24 by law.
25 SECTION 5. A NEW SECTION OF KRS CHAPTER 433 IS CREATED TO
26 READ AS FOLLOWS:
27 (1) A license issued by the commission may be revoked or suspended by the
Page 5 of 53
BR123800.100 - 1238 - XXXX 3/11/2026 3:19 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1238
1 commission, subject to appeal pursuant to KRS Chapter 13B, for the following
2 reasons:
3 (a) Fraud, misrepresentation, or false statement contained in the license
4 application;
5 (b) Fraud, misrepresentation, or false statements made while conducting
6 business as a secondary metals recycler;
7 (c) A person is a fugitive or has been convicted of a criminal offense within the
8 preceding three (3) years involving business or commercial fraud, extortion,
9 or receiving stolen property;
10 (d) Any condition or fact that would have resulted in denial of the original
11 license application; or
12 (e) Conducting business as a secondary metals recycler under this chapter in
13 an unlawful manner or in a manner that endangers public health, safety, or
14 welfare.
15 (2) The commission shall give reasonable notice of the revocation or suspension to
16 the secondary metals recycler at the address listed in the application for licensure.
17 (3) Any secondary metals recycler whose license is revoked or suspended shall
18 immediately surrender the license to the commission.
19 (4) If a licensee is a firm or corporation, it shall be sufficient cause for the denial,
20 suspension, or revocation of a license that any officer, director, or trustee of the
21 firm or corporation, or any member in case of a partnership, has been guilty of
22 any act or omission which would be cause for refusing, suspending, or revoking a
23 license to the party as an individual. Each licensee shall be responsible for the
24 acts of any or all of his or her employees while acting as his or her agent, if the
25 licensee approved of or had knowledge of the acts and after approval or
26 knowledge retained the benefit, proceeds, profits, or advantages accruing from
27 the acts.
