9 Section 14. KRS 514.110 is amended to read as follows:
10 (1) A person is guilty of receiving stolen property when he or she receives, retains, or
11 disposes of movable property of another knowing that it has been stolen, or having
12 reason to believe that it has been stolen, unless the property is received, retained, or
13 disposed of with intent to restore it to the owner.
14 (2) The following shall be prima facie evidence that a person knew property was
15 stolen:
16 (a) A person possessed recently stolen movable property; or
17 (b) A secondary metals recycler as defined in Section 1 of this Act intentionally
18 failed to enter a report of a transaction into the LeadsOnline database or
19 maintain the information in a register pursuant to Section 10 of this
20 Act[possession by any person of any recently stolen movable property shall be
21 prima facie evidence that such person knew such property was stolen].
22 (3) Receiving stolen property is a Class B misdemeanor unless:
23 (a) The value of the property is five hundred dollars ($500) or more but less than
24 one thousand dollars ($1,000), in which case it is a Class A misdemeanor;
25 (b) The value of the property is one thousand dollars ($1,000) or more but less
26 than ten thousand dollars ($10,000), in which case it is a Class D felony;
27 (c) A person has three (3) or more convictions under paragraph (a) of this
Page 16 of 53
BR123800.100 - 1238 - XXXX 3/11/2026 3:19 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1238
1 subsection within the last five (5) years, in which case it is a Class D felony.
2 The five (5) year period shall be measured from the dates on which the
3 offenses occurred for which the judgments of conviction were entered;
4 (d) The value of the property is ten thousand dollars ($10,000) or more, in which
5 case it is a Class C felony;
6 (e) The property is a firearm, regardless of the value of the firearm, in which case
7 it is a Class D felony;
8 (f) The property is anhydrous ammonia, regardless of the value of the ammonia,
9 in which case it is a Class D felony unless it is proven that the person violated
10 this section with the intent to manufacture methamphetamine in violation of
11 KRS 218A.1432, in which case it is a Class B felony for the first offense and
12 a Class A felony for each subsequent offense; or
13 (g) The offense occurs during a declared emergency as defined by KRS 39A.020
14 arising from a natural or man-made disaster, within the area covered by the
15 emergency declaration, and within the area impacted by the disaster, in which
